To sum up, it‚Äôs clear why the tale of Dobrynia and the Dragon is so popular since it has a perfect mix of traditional and original elements which makes it an exciting read/listen.

The traditional tale of saving the princess is all about the said princess, but in this story we have Dobrynia rescuing countless other people from the dragon‚Äôs offsprings which elevates him as a national hero.

The second half of the tale happens after a timeskip. Despite the plot itself being a bit more interesting due to the secret nest reveal at the end it‚Äôs still a classic story of a hero killing the dragon and saving the princess. Tales like this never went out of fashion and were some of the fist ones humans shared with each other.

The first battle was to be the last with the hero just killed the dragon, but later the plot expended and we got the serpent‚Äôs oath and Dobrynia sparing it‚Äôs life. This made the tale more unique, but also created an inner contradiction. In their first battle Dobrynia wins quickly despite being literally naked and outside of his element and then, in the second half, they fight for hours (days in other versions) despite the hero being fully armed this time and standing on solid ground.

Some would claim that unlike the primordial Chaos serpent the dragon of this tale is winged and can breath fire which seemingly doesn‚Äôt the aquatic nature of the archetype. But we have to consider that the dragon fights Dobrynia in the river. Their second battle is in the deep mountain caves. Plenty of water in both cases. Plus, only the first part of the tale has remnants of the cosmic myth anyway.

Even though I am usually against trying to find remnants of the myth in the folk tales this is a rare exception since here the traces of the cosmic Chaoskampf are too obvious to ignore. In the river encounter Dobrynia takes the place of Perun while the dragon of the mountain is a stand-in for the primordial Chaos serpent. The use of club (or some other blunt object) is also noteworthy.

The first part of the tale provides a more interesting material for analysis. Dobrynia‚Äôs father was old and died before the boy grew up. The widow took good care of the child, in fact Dobrynia is a rather unique character for folk tales since he didn‚Äôt grow up in a poor villager‚Äôs family and got proper education. He can both read and write which wasn‚Äôt as common back then.

Those who read/heard the tale will agree that it can be split in two parts both culminating in Dobrynia defeating the dragon, but despite featuring the same hero and villain those two halves are very different.

Analysis of the tale of Dobrynia and the Dragon of the mountain Out of all Slavic epic songs this is one of the most complicated, despite the simplicity of the plot. The reason for the complexity is that it combines ancient and more modern elements which is not that rare, but said elements themselves are rather peculiar.

To sum up, European Thunderer archetype is traditionally armed with an oak club and a bow with limitless arrows (possibly throwing stones).

In fact, belemnite guards have been connected to the Thunder Gods by many Europeans. Before being identified as fossils they were often believed to be thunderbolts thrown from the sky. In Germanic folklore, belemnites are known by different names, such as Devil's finger or Donar‚Äôs stones (Donderstenen) and were kept in houses to protect from lightning.
Slavic Perun is also depicted with a bow and there was a belief that belemnite guards were his arrows fallen on the ground. Unfinished sketch by BrotherBjorn
Indra‚Äôs primary weapons are Vajra club and a bow called Vijaya. In modern Hinduism this bow is mostly attributed to Shiva even though this is just due to the erosion of original tradition.

Some argue that originally the long-ranged weapon of the Thunderer was actually his primary one and was a simple rock. I agree that it could have been the original sidearm, but not the main one which was the club. For example, in some versions of the myth Hercules killed Hydra by hurling stones at her.

Romans had a belief that the lightning is taken back to Zeus by the eagle. Even though Zeus himself wasn‚Äôt the Thunder God it still proves that this projectile/long-range weapon was a major element of Thunder God iconography.

In some traditions it has merged into an idea of the God throwing his primary weapon and it magically returning to him. As West wrote: "Either he gets his unique weapon back each time, or he has an inexhaustible supply of ammunition." We know that Mjollnir returns to Thor of its own.

The Thunderer‚Äôs bow Forgotten weapon One of the mostly ignored elements of traditional Thunder God iconography is his bow.
Roman Hercule‚Äôs club amulet

I didn‚Äôt bring up any Hindu Gods, but there‚Äôs plenty of proof for the club-wielding Thunderer there. Indra has his Vajra, which is definitely a club albeit a weird one. Another ancient deity Balarama, though mostly associated with farming, is also a god of great strength and a club-wielder too.

To sum up, the original weapon of the European Thunder God archetype is an oak club no-one else can wield, but due to various different reasons some Europeans tribes reimagined it to be some other weapon.

Hercules, when lying on his funeral pyre gifts his bow to his friend Philoctetes, but the club burns with him since only Hercules can use it: Let this club,‚Äù he said, ‚Äúwhich no hand but mine has wielded, burn in the flames with me; this weapon alone shall follow Hercules. This also shouldst thou have,‚Äù said he, ‚Äúif thou couldst wield it. Let it add fuel to its master‚Äôs pyre.‚Äù

One of the most important aspects of the Thunderer‚Äôs weapon is that no one else can wield it. Mjolnir is well known for Thor being the only one who can use it thanks to his protective gloves and great strength.
Irish Dagda, a deity who combines elements of traditional Thunderer, Shaman and Sky-Father also has a wooden club.

Also, remember donarkeule. A Donar (Thor) associated amulet which predates the Viking-Age hammers. Though I can agree that it was a Roman influence, Germanic tribes still associated it with their deity right away.

In Gesta Danorum Saxo tells that Thor wields a club made from oak: "But Thor shattered all their shield-defences with the terrific swings of his club, calling on his enemies to attack him as much as his comrades support him. There was no armour which could stand up to his strokes, nor anyone who could survive them. Shields, helmets, everything he drove at with his oak cudgel was crushed on impact, nor were bodily size or muscle any protection." Some try to brush it off as interpetatio romana, but considering that all other Thunderers have clubs it‚Äôs a weak defense. Or maybe you want to tell me that Saxo just invented something about a club-wielding Thor and it just happened to coincide with other Gods of Thunder from places Saxo didn‚Äôt even know of?
What about the most popular (sadly due to hollywood shlock) European Thunder God? Thor is well known for using a hammer called Mjolnir as his signature weapon. But was this always the case?

Slavic Perun is also a club wielder and was always traditionally depicted as such. Sadly some modern Slavic Pagans are not aware of that and think of him as a God with an axe which is one of many modern fallacies traced back to early rodnover movement.
Hercules is the best example of a Thunder God with a club, but he is far from the only one. In fact, I‚Äôll now argue that originally all of used wooden clubs.

Thunderer‚Äôs weapon of choice It‚Äôs well know that European Thunder Gods are very similar. All of them share such features as: thunder and lightning, masculinity, physical power, important place in pantheon and a signature weapon. The latter also bare heavy resemblance being blunt and heavy. It is theorized that originally the European Thunderer archetype had a wooden club, the first weapon of both men and Gods.

The veneration of Ded stone continued. In 1904 volkhv Sevastei died. He had an extremely long life (100+ yeas) and stayed strong and healthy to his final breath. Alongside the other local Pagans Sevastei was buried separately from everyone else. By the 20th century Ded stood alone. His old companion Volot was no more. Even the fire was taken down. The kapishe itself was destroyed completely in 1905. But, people still came to pray to the stone. In 1920s Sevastei‚Äôs son took his father‚Äôs place. Even though the kapishe was destroyed young Sevastei took priestly duties as all men in his family did before him. Sadly, he was repressed and murdered by communists in 1927. He was the last Sevastei. In the beginning of 1980s Ded was taken to the park known as Museum of Stone. There he stands to this day. Even though some proposed the reconstruction of the kapishe, the idea went nowhere (so far).

Tragedy and destruction In 1870s there were some cases of anti-pagan activity. The police came, extinguished the fire and prohibited animal sacrifices, but Sevastei managed to bribe them. Later judeo-christian priests decided to take the stone from Sevastei and baptize him. In 1880 before the celebration of 900 years since the baptism of Rus the police came to stop Sevastei‚Äôs ritual. They extinguished the fired and chopped down the ancient oak. They‚Äôve beaten Sevastei, confiscated the stone and all his sacred artifacts and erected a cross as well as plates for monetary offerings. This is how the most enduring Pagan temple of all Europe was destroyed. A crime we will never forget. A christian priest by the name Jafimy took Sevastei‚Äôs place. He later turned out to be a criminal (a former thief and bandit) and fled with the money he earned from the followers. Very christian.

Minsk kapishe also had a well with sacred water used for healing which helped make some money for the priest. Yes, you read right, a real pagan priest was looking after the kapishe and conducting rituals (such as divination). It was a hereditary position and all priests had the same name Sevastei which they accepted with their duties. In 1850s Sevastei was a tall, large man with a big beard. He carried out his duties and even created handmade clay fetishes in a form of a rooster for locals to take home, put in a sacred corner and pray to. Sevastei lived in a very ancient wooden hut close to the kapishe. People came with simple wishes like healing, marriage, childbirth or divination. Rushniks (a handmade piece of cloth embroidered with traditional symbols) were hanged on the stone (and sometimes the oak too). Ded was practically covered with rushniks.

Ded Stone of Minsk One of the most well know and venerated sacred stones in Slavic paganism is the Ded Stone (ded means old man) from Minsk, Belarus. This is the story of this pagan artifact. Initially this sacred stone stood in the kapishe (open air temple) on the banks of Svisloch river. The interesting part is that this kapishe was operational all the way up to the 1920s! This is the last ancient pagan temple in all Europe. The stone stood right next to a tree in the centre of kapishe to it was a giant, sacred oak locals called Volot (which means giant) which was prayed to and decorated. The oak was growing there up to 1888. There also was a big sacrificial flame where things like giblets were burned. There also used to be a second flame there, closer to the stone, but it collapsed and the above mentioned one was build. The whole area was fenced with wicker.

Perhaps the existence of 'gods of the pouch', (small scale statuettes), which were not known in the Early and Middle Viking Age, is a special phenomenon that emerged with the decline of paganism and the beginning of Christian supremacy. It is quite possible that the tradition of manufacturing 'gods of the pouch', in the image of unidentified pagan gods continued in the marginal pagan regions of north-eastern Europe, where a number of small figurines (so called 'images of Perun'- one of the pagan gods in the Ancient Rus') have been found. The exile allows the hero to find a wife outside of the clan and create a new one which is why protagonists of ancient stories end up with women they met during the travels. The latter always involves great deeds like saving the future wife from monsters. It‚Äôs very likely that originally Kozarin saved the maiden (who obviously wasn‚Äôt his sister) from dragons instead of Tatars. There are some versions where we see exactly that, also in others the Tatars have a pet dragon who kidnaps the girl. If we examine the image of Tatars in bylinas in general they were a faceless horde of conquerors, which shows how ill-fitting small-scale banditry is for them in the tale of Kozarin. Tatars here are just a stand-in for the (mostly) forgotten monsters of the original. The latter is a common tend and we will see more of this monsters turned into humans villains (often stopping halfway) when analyzing other tales.

Analysis of the tale of Kozarin The core of this tale is an ancient one, but there are relatively modern elements weaved into the plot which makes it a good example of how Slavic bylina tends to mix something bordering on tribalism with contemporary motifs. Kozarin‚Äôs backstory is short, but very important since it shows him to be a forgotten archetype of an exiled hero. In the ancient epics the protagonist often lives as an outcast and/or gets exiled from his tribe, not due to crimes, but rather because he's a larger than life figure and can‚Äôt fit in the established hierarchy.

The thing about all folk tales is that everyone tells them differently. The basic plot is always the same, but the details change from one storyteller to another which can really effect the plot‚Äôs focus. Even my retellings are not just compilations. I‚Äôve analyzed the tale in different variations and allowed it to pass through myself which left a unique mark. This is the beauty of folklore. A lot of said beauty is lost due to me telling the tales in prose. It's a major issue since the ancient poetic tradition is almost lost.

Together they return to the same old village Mykhailo grew up in, but he does not enter it. The sister wants Kozarin to come too, but he declines: "Return to your home and I will return to mine". The steppe is his home now.

Initially Kozarin and the maiden want to get married, but as they are riding to the girl‚Äôs home it turns out that she is his sister, but this only makes Kozarin even happier since he got to save his kin.
Right in the middle of Tatars‚Äô argument Kozarin swoops in on his horse and quickly kills them all.
Kozarin rushes to where the raven told him and soon sees enemy tents as well as a fair maiden tied up and crying. The Tatars are arguing over which one of them will take her.

One day Mykhailo was tired after the hunt. He stops to rest under a big oak tree and notices a raven on it‚Äôs branch. Kozarin pulls his bow and aims, but just before the shot the raven speaks. He says that there are three Tatars nearby who have kidnapped a girl and want to torture her.

The tale of Mykhailo Kozarin Our hero was born in a big peasant family. His parents were too poor to raise Mykhailo themselves and didn‚Äôt care for the unwanted child. An old lady who had no kids of her own and lived alone was the one who took the child in and raised him with love. When Kozarin turns 17 he decides to leave his village. He bids farewell to the foster mother and even visits his real parents since Kozarin never hated them, though they don‚Äôt care for him. He lives in the wild for years hunting beasts, drinking spring water and sleeping under the stars. The steppe is his home now.
Today I will tell you one of Slavic poetic tales. The analysis will come tomorrow.

What we have just read is possibly an alternative version of Ragnarok myth. Just like in the one we all know Thor dies after defeating a giant serpent (nameless here). Then the entire world is destroyed returning to the primordial sea of chaos and darkness, but eventually life finds a way and begins anew. The earth dries up and the new cycle begins.

After the earth had dried up again, two lakes were left behind, which are as deep as the world. And the one was called the Uttiloch, and the other the Lake of the Gods or White Lake. And the place where the goats fell was called Animals (Dieren).

The tall oak creaked and plunged into the depths with its burden. From the scorching fire of lightning rose a vile stench of the scorching poison. The golden head of the Thunder God smoked in dirty brown clouds. He staggered in his chariot and swooned backwards, swooning. With a terrible blow he fell from heaven to the ground near the spot where he had crushed the serpent. It was as if the universe was torn apart and the world was torn from its seams. His empty chariot behind the runaway driverless bucks, roared furiously along the cloud road, crashing at last on Thunder Mountain. Then there was silence and the earth sank into the sea. Far over the fields of surging waters night descended and towering the waves billowed their foam tops.

The Winter Giants gathered in the forest, and there enlisted the aid of the great monster serpent, whose deadening breath discolored and withered the leaves of the trees, and where it had crawled, poisonous fungi arose. In that forest of bright red and poisonous yellow the giants made an alliance with the serpent. The trees were so moved by this terrible treaty that they shed many leaves. The next day the serpent writhed around the tallest oak tree to vomit its venom into the sky, and the giants threw hail with hands full. From all sides Thunar now gathered his great cloud masses to block the entrance. From far over the endless cloud fields he himself came riding in his wildly rolling chariot, strung with two black bucks. His beard flapped in the wind like a red flag, and the bucks whipped sparks from the pavement with their hooves. The whole sky was on fire and sledgehammers resounded that shook the earth.

It was at the time when the giants stormed the sky and a great serpent dwelt in the Uunnilo. The rough giants - vassals of the mighty Winter Giant - had begun the battle against the Summer Gods. They spice up the Woldbergen with sand from the wolf's chamber; but Thunar the mighty Thunder God still held them in check. Already some autumn mists fluttered over the forests, like gray vanes of the approaching winter army, and great cloud wolves wrestled with the Sun God. The Thunderer then growled furiously in his red beard, so that the giants fainted for a while. The herons and the swallows, terrified and frightened by the incipient battle, fled southward on swift blades.

Let us return to Slavic material for one last argument. We know the Weles was very likely to be a God of the Underworld akin to Greek Hades. And how does the Underworld look in Slavic fairy tales? It‚Äôs a deep underground kingdom where everything is made out of precious stones and metals. This is the final golden nail in the coffin of Weles as God of cattle fallacy. Now we can finally see Weles as ancient Slavs did, a God of Wealth and Afterlife.

Germanic Fehu rune has the exact same double meaning of cattle and wealth as Proto-Slavic "—Å–∫–æ—Ç". This is because both Germanic and Slavic tribes obviously saw great value in their cattle and actively traded it as a (mobile) wealth.

Now, having properly analyzed the sources, let us turn to non-Slavic material for some comparison. Germanic Wotan who, as I wrote before in a short series of comparison posts, is a deity similar to Weles (though much more important in his pantheon). Scythian genetics: Once again, be wary of genetics disinformation published by South Asians. They often use cherrypicked samples to spin a narrative ‚Äî usually some sort of anti-White or anti-European bias. This Twitter poster has selectively chosen two of the most East-Asian-shifted Scythian populations and presented them as average Scythians. In reality, Scythians had varying levels of East Asian admixture, ranging from 0% in Europe to 50% in the Altai regions. They were not a homogeneous ethnic group. They can be roughly divided into three genetic clusters: 1. Western Scythians, who were near-identical to modern Eastern Europeans. 2. Central Scythians (Sarmatians, Cimmerians, Tian Shan Sakas, Tagar, etc), most closely related to modern Russians, Finnic peoples (e.g. Udmurts), and Pamiri Tajiks. 3. Eastern Scythians (Pazyryk, Kazakh Sakas, etc.), most similar to modern Central Asians, e.g. Uzbeks and Bashkirs. I wrote an *unbiased* article on Scythian culture and genetics earlier this year.
